<br>
2)  As such, I do apologize for laughing at Ruhi's claim.<br>
<br>
3)  But, if such an ICE worked with EQ, then EQ has failed to suitably protect logic routines by having them on the server rather than client in my opinion.  (In other words, this means the server accepts results from the client rather than cues.)<br>
<br>
4)  In which case the assurances given to me during beta were at best misleading.<br>
<br>
Online game programmers, specifically those in the realm of multiplayer interactive games with a persistant element, have known or should have known that the only way to obtain a &quot;hack resistant&quot; game environment where players depend on the game code to keep a level playing field insofar as the game mechanics themselves are applied, is to limit or remove client logic.<br>
<br>
That this is not the case seriously undermines the stability of the platform as a &quot;judge&quot; device.<br>
<br>
5)  As to your comment that &quot;Dude, nobody in AD uses Trainers... I know people in BoK have. I dont know if they continue to do so, but I know it was done.&quot; let me start here:  Name the person.  I would seriously like to know.  Tell me in game if ya like.  On the other hand, I can specifically name a member of AD who was banned for their use now, as that info was given to me to solidify the claim these programs exist.<br>
<br>
Thus your statement, claiming AD is free of such use, and then attacking BOK on alleged past use while AD members specifically in the past have been banned as such, does little to credit your claim or your guild.<br>
<br>
I state that in response to you.  However, Adell assures me that such use has been rejected by AD to the extent possible by peers.  I am hoping this is the case.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hackability&quot; of a game removes the desire for me to play.  Who the hell would want to sit at a game of poker knowing some people there had means to see your cards?<br>
<br>
Not I.<br>
<br>
To help counter this, Adell has pointed out that the patch in recent memory that shortly after resulted in mass bannings for 3rd party software may mean that Verant is better able to detect and then act on such hacking.  If this is the case, then they have a reactive response that may minimize damage until...<br>
<br>
Luclin's &quot;new engine&quot; may address many of the material client logic issues that now distress me.  Rather than flat out quit as I thought I might do (again, who wants to play in hackfest when you dont have the means to compete legitimately?) I'm going to give VI the benefit of the doubt and play for at least a short time after Luclin and decide then.<br>
<br>
6) Your next claim is spread between two replies so I consolidate them here:<br>
&quot;And yes, Brilbane was stolen from Belayne. Bel bought the acct from the guy and the mother fucker stole it. So that in itself will keep people from FS killing that cocksucker. . . Hmmmm... if the acct wasnt jacked from Bel, how would I know the Username is davidrhill?&quot;<br>
<br>
I will give just one scenario that should address this, my only position is that you do not condemn someone on the claims of a biased party that gains from those claims:<br>
<br>
Assume Bril and Bel are so-so pals.  At some point in time Bril and Bel share account info to advance mutual goals, such as securing a res, or CR, or helping exp, or twink, whatever.  I am certain that many people who do not know eachother in real life have shared account info on nothing more than &quot;knowing&quot; eachother in game.<br>
<br>
Assume further that these two drifted apart, or became hostile to one another.  Again, we have seen that former allies can become enemies with simple twists of fate in game, no?<br>
<br>
This would leave Bel with the account name of Bril, who then says &quot;Bril was stolen from me, I can prove it! His account name is 'davidrhill'!&quot;<br>
<br>
Or lets change this a bit.  Bril trades his account for Bor, over time, Bor becomes bored with his &quot;Bril&quot; account and sells it to Bel, who perhaps is unaware.  Then Bor, not having a character, ganks back from Bril the &quot;Bor&quot; account.  Bril, now screwed by Bor and based on the even account trade, ganks back the &quot;Bril&quot; account.  Leaving Bril with Bril, Bor with Bor and Bel's cash, and Bel with no account and out cash.<br>
<br>
In neither example would Bril be the &quot;evil doer&quot;.<br>
<br>
7)  If you are going to trade or sell your account, be wary of who you get in bed with.  Be safe, get a contract that can be reasonably established and enforced.  Even if it cannot secure ACCESS to the account, it does facilitate actions to seek redress in the real world.<br>
<br>
